<F P=100> NAFTA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mercosur To Negotiate NAFTA Entry as Bloc </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103213694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2012 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1103213694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 10 Mar (EFE) -- Argentina, Brazil, 
Paraguay, and Uruguay -- the countries that are partners in the 
Common Market of the South (Mercosur) -- have decided to ratify 
that they will negotiate as a bloc their possible joining of the 
North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) between the United 
States, Canada, and Mexico. 
  Argentine Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella said that the 
decision "is the most important political fact" in the meeting 
of the ministers of economy and foreign affairs of the Mercosur 
countries, which ended today in Buenos Aires. 
  "There are ways to make Mercosur compatible with NAFTA, and 
this is what we are studying," Di Tella added. 
  The deliberations in Buenos Aires seem to have given 
definition to the Argentine position, which at one point was 
considering the possibility of unilaterally joining NAFTA upon 
invitation by the United States. 
  The Mercosur countries will now study how to reactivate the 
negotiations known as "four plus one," begun two years ago, that 
aim at approaching the North American commercial bloc. 
  The Mercosur ministers also agreed to study all the options 
for promoting broad regional economic integration, on the basis 
of a Brazilian proposal to create the South American Free Trade 
Association (ALCSA). 
  The ministers avoided, however, resuming discussions on the 
Mexican decision to refrain from extending the concessions 
obtained within NAFTA to the other Latin American countries, 
diplomatic sources have said. 
  The matter, which has been a source of conflict, has been 
awaiting resolution since the last Latin American Integration 
Association (ALADI) meeting held in Montevideo in February. 
  The proposal to create ALCSA, which was raised in October 
1993, was formally presented to the Mercosur ministers by the 
Brazilian ministers of finance and of foreign affairs, Fernando 
Henrique Cardoso and Celso Amorim respectively. 
  Cardoso told EFE that the initiative "does not go against 
anybody, and seeks to preserve the Latin American bloc and 
strengthen regional commerce," thus denying that it is an 
attempt "to put the brakes on a commercial invasion" by NAFTA 
members. 
  Brazil, South America's most developed country, sells 13 
percent of its exports to Mercosur and 8 percent to the other 
South American countries. 
  Cardoso said that his country has not considered the 
possibility of joining NAFTA "because we cannot take the 
initiative; we have not been invited." 
  "The idea is to promote commercial liberalization, but 
always 
on the basis of the consolidation of Mercosur as an 
institutional structure and as an organization for joint 
negotiations for the entire continent," Uruguayan Foreign 
Minister Sergio Abreu said. 
  Uruguay maintains that "everything is compatible, provided 
the obligations assumed under Mercosur are complied with and 
provided there is a common foreign policy toward third 
countries." 
  The Brazilians proposed that the South American Free Trade 
Zone come into operation 10 years after 1 January 1995, the day 
when Mercosur will become fully operational. Mercosur is 
considered the "nucleus" of the integration process. 
  This means that Mercosur commercial policies should be 
coordinated with those of the Andean Pact, which is made up of 
Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Venezuela, and with 
Chilean policies. 
  The Mercosur area has a population of 190 million people, 
with a gross domestic product equivalent to slightly more than 
50 percent of Latin America's total GDP. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

