<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   12 March Agenda Outlined </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1203141594 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0811 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1203141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Santiago, 12 Mar (EFE) -- Today Chilean 
President Eduardo Frei Ruiz Tagle, who took over on 11 March, 
will announce the main guidelines of his administration which 
will have the support of the same political alliance that backed 
up his predecessor Patricio Aylwin. 
  Rather than talking about "continuity," however, the new 
administration is announcing "new times", innovations and new 
initiatives. [passage omitted] 
  Interior Minister German Correa, from the Socialist Party, 
has announced that in the speech Frei will make today "he will 
outline the key objectives of his administration." 
  One of the main differences between Aylwin and Frei, a 
militant Christian Democrat just like his predecessor, is that 
the Frei has appointed a Socialist as interior minister and 
chief of cabinet. 
  Correa will also play the role of vice president whenever 
President Frei travels abroad. [passsage omitted] 
  Yet another difference between Aylwin and Frei is that the 
latter did not ask or receive suggestions from political parties 
that make up the government coalition for the appointment of 
ministers, under secretaries and other government officials. 
This attitude displeased several people, even some members of 
the Christian Democratic Party, the largest component of the 
ruling coalition. 
  Today's presidential agenda includes several bilateral 
meetings with visiting dignitaries, beginning with Peruvian 
President Alberto Fujimori. Later on Frei will meet with 
Brazilian President Itamar Franco, Paraguayan President Juan 
Carlos Wasmosy, and OAS Secretary General Joao Baena Soares. 
  The meetings will continue throughout the afternoon and at 
the end of the day there will be a rally at Plaza Constitucion, 
right in front of La Moneda Palace. On this occasion President 
Frei will make a speech in which he will outline the objectives 
of his 6-year term in office. 
  [Santiago Television Nacional de Chile Imagen Internacional 
in Spanish at 1259 GMT on 12 March reports that "at 1115 local 
time (1415 GMT) President Frei will briefly attend a reception 
at the Santiago City Hall and will begin his meetings with 
foreign dignitaries at 1130 local time. The formal reception 
that President Frei will offer to special guests at Plaza 
Constitucion will last from 2030 to 2300 local time."] 

</TEXT>

