<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Accord With IMF Delayed; Mission to Visit U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1303003094 Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 10 
Mar 94 p 8 </F>

<F P=103> PY1303003094 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo FOLHA DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Carlos Alberto Sardenberg] </F>
  [Text] Finance Minister Fernando Henrique Cardoso should be 
going to Washington next week to conclude the negotiations with 
the International Monetary Fund. An agreement with the IMF is a 
precondition for signing an accord for rescheduling the debt 
that Brazil owes to private banks. 
  An IMF mission that was in Brasilia discussing the Brazilian 
Government budget yesterday returned to the United States 
without having made a final decision. Economic Policy Secretary 
Winston Fritsch said there is no more disagreement about 
figures. A Brazilian technical mission will just the same visit 
Washington over the weekend to arrange the final details. 
Brazilian accounts are not easy to understand, if nothing else 
because the inflation rate is never known. 
  According to the foreign debt agreement timetable, the 
agreement with the IMF should have been ready on 10 March. The 
delay, which will be of approximately one week, was caused by 
the Brazilian Government's delay -- Congress is also responsible 
for it -- in voting on the Social Emergency Fund and the other 
measures for balancing public accounts. 
  Furthermore, the accounts of a country with a high, chronic, 
and diversified inflation rate are a mess. Which inflation rate 
should be considered, that in cruzeiros -- which will disappear 
-- or that in reals -- the new currency? There are complex 
exchanges of funds between different government organs. The 
Central Bank, for example, makes profits through monetary 
correction of securities from the Treasury, which is the debtor. 
Yet the Central Banks returns this money to the Treasury, and 
the accounts are thus neutralized. In the middle of all these 
figures an IMF technician said during one of the sessions: "I 
am totally lost." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

