<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Senate Approves Appointments To Control Prices </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103210994 Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO in Portuguese 4 Mar 94 p 
4 </F>

<F P=103> PY1103210994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro O GLOBO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brasilia -- On 3 March the Brazilian Senate approved 
the appointment of Ruy Coutinho do Nascimento as chairman of the 
Administrative Council for Economic Defense (CADE), and of 
Alkimar Moura as head of monetary policy of the Central Bank. 
Coutinho obtained 46 votes, with three votes against him and 
two abstentions, while Alkimar obtained 40 votes, seven against 
and two abstentions. CADE is one of Finance Minister Henrique 
Cardoso's main instruments to control oligopolies and cartels. 
It will resort to the antitrust law to prosecute, on behalf of 
the government, company directors who set excessive prices for 
their products. If found guilty, these directors may go to 
prison. 

</TEXT>

