<F P=106> [From the "TV Today" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Colombian Government welcomed gladly today the 
report that two additional alleged Valle del Cauca drug 
traffickers had surrendered. They are Julio Fabio Urdinola 
Grajales, brother of Ivan Urdinola Grajales, and Jesus Ancizar 
Porras, who were interned at Palmira Prison, Valle del Cauca 
Department, where they will negotiate their penalties with the 
Prosecutor General's Office. 
  Urdinola Grajales arrived with his defense counsels and 
immediately was received by Regional Prosecutor Francisco Javier 
Hernandez and Palmira Prison Director Marco Antonio de Moya. 
During the legal proceedings after undergoing a medical 
checkup, Urdinola Grajales confessed to his participation in 
drug-trafficking activities. 
  [Begin recording] [Unidentified reporter] Will the police or 
Army be in charge of security? 
  [Captain Raul Benavides, Valle del Cauca police commander] 
It 
is the prison director's duty; we will back him up, however. 
[end recording] 
  Ancizar Porras arrived with Urdinola Grajales and confessed 
to his participation in crimes related to manslaughter. 
  [Begin recording] [Justice Minister Andres Gonzalez Diaz] 
This is an important and interesting event in the country's 
struggle against drug trafficking and organized crime; in 
addition, it underlines the fact it is more intelligent to 
surrender to the authorities than to perish as the result of the 
state's unceasing and determined actions. 
  [Prosecutor General Gustavo de Greiff] This is the result of 
a process in which the administration of justice, the 
government, and the police have cooperated. All of this has led 
to this surrender, and I hope it will also lead to other 
surrenders. [end recording] 
  Both Urdinola Grajales and Ancizar Porras will be held at 
Palmira Prison, where they will negotiate with the Prosecutor 
General's Office a quick end to the process they initiated with 
their surrender today. 

</TEXT>

