<H3> <TI>   President Casts Vote in Legislative Elections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1303212994 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1303212994 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [from the "NTC Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] President Cesar Gaviria Trujillo was the first 
citizen to cast his vote. With his wife Ana Milena Munoz 
present, he produced a copy of his identification card and cast 
his vote for the Senate, Chamber of Representatives, and Liberal 
Party presidential candidate elections. The president ruled out 
a break in relations with Cuba in the wake of an alleged meeting 
of Colombian guerrillas on the Caribbean island: 
  [Begin Gaviria recording] It is obvious in international 
relations we cannot take action until facts are verified. [end 
recording] 
  The president termed as positive the surrender to justice of 
alleged drug trafficker Julio Fabio Urdinola. Gaviria said he 
hopes the Prosecutor General's Office and the Justice Ministry 
will smooth out their differences. 
  [Begin Gaviria recording, in progress] ...that we will be 
able to reach an agreement with the Prosecutor General's Office. 
[end recording] 
  President Gaviria will remain at Narino Palace with his 
minister to monitor the elections. 

</TEXT>

