<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Authorities Released </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1403030894 Hamburg DPA in Spanish 0159 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1403030894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 13 Mar (DPA) -- Thirty-two 
electoral authorities who were kidnapped by guerrillas before 
today's congressional elections in Colombia were released 
tonight (local time) in the eastern Department of Santander, 
according to press sources. 
  Members of the pro-Cuban Army of National Liberation (ELN) 
perpetrated the mass kidnapping. This action prevented the 
holding of elections in the small town of Carcasi. 
  The rebels intercepted a bus and took seven members of the 
National Civil Registry Office, which organized the elections, 
and 25 students who were going to act as voting officers in that 
locality, to an unknown destination. 
  During the past month, groups linked to the Simon Bolivar 
Guerrilla Coordinating Board (CGSB) intensified their attacks to 
sabotage the legislative elections, although the government said 
today those attempts failed. 
  In addition to kidnapping electoral authorities, the CGSB 
also kidnapped three government officials in Cesar Department, 
blew up a stretch of the country's main oil pipeline, attacked 
intermunicipal buses, and activated medium-intensity bombs that 
did not cause any victims. 
  Colombians renewed today 102 Senate seats and 163 in the 
Chamber of Representatives (deputies) and elected Ernesto Samper 
as presidential candidate for the Liberal Party, which used the 
opportunity to hold an internal "popular primary." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

