<F P=100> Paraguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Wasmosy Supports Colombia's Gaviria as OAS Head </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1203222494 Asuncion NOTICIAS in Spanish 12 Mar 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> PY1203222494 </F>
<F P=104>  Asuncion NOTICIAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Santiago, Chile -- Paraguay will support the 
candidacy of Colombian President Cesar Gaviria to become the OAS 
secretary general. This confirmation was made yesterday by 
President Juan Carlos Wasmosy, during an approximately 20-minute 
meeting with Gaviria at the Carreras Hotel in Santiago. 
  It has also been learned that the U.S. assistant secretary 
of 
state for inter-American affairs, Alexander Watson, asked 
Paraguay to vote for Gaviria, whose efforts in the struggle 
against drug trafficking and the Colombian mafia have satisfied 
Washington. 
  "We confirmed our support for him," said Wasmosy after the 
meeting with Gaviria, even though the previous administration of 
General Andres Rodriguez had promised its support to Costa Rican 
Foreign Minister Paul Niheaus, who is also here in Santiago 
holding meetings seeking support. 
  NOTICIAS talked with Gaviria on his desire to become OAS 
secretary general. Gaviria said he hopes the result of the 
final elections in the OAS will serve to strengthen that 
inter-American organization. 
  He said: "I have great confidence in their maturity, in how 
the countries value my representation and what I can do as 
leader of OAS." 
  Asked about the pressure the United States is reportedly 
exerting in favor of his candidacy, he said: "I believe the 
United States is simply expressing the opinion it has always 
held on the qualifications I may have for holding that position. 
That or any other country of the Americas has the right to 
express an opinion publicly." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

