<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   UN Secretary General Arrives on 4-Day Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1403152194 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1650 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1403152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 13 Mar (NA) -- Arriving on an official 
four-day visit today, UN Secretary General Butrus Butrus-Ghali 
emphasized Argentina's significant role in the UN peace-keeping 
projects. 
  He arrived this morning at the Ezeiza international airport. 
He will ask Argentine President Carlos Menem to send more 
troops to former Yugoslavia during a meeting tomorrow. 
  In remarks to a Buenos Aires newspaper, Butrus-Ghali noted 
that the United Nations wants the Argentine Government to send 
an additional battalion of blue helmets to join those already in 
Croatia. 
  Foreign Minister Guido Di Tella welcomed the Egyptian 
diplomat, emphasized the "esteemed value" of the visit, and 
confirmed Argentina's desire to continue participating in the UN 
peace-keeping missions. 
  Issues like the UN debt following the various deployments of 
Argentine blue helmets will also be discussed during the visit. 
  The formation of an international force to struggle against 
hunger -- the White Helmets -- will also be reviewed. 
  During the meeting with Menem tomorrow, an agreement to 
assist the Mothers, Infants, and Nutrition Program [Programa 
Materno Infantil y Nutricion] (PROMIN), financed by the World 
Bank, will also be signed. 

</TEXT>

