<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fruit Exporters Back U.S. Court Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103183394 Santiago EL MERCURIO in Spanish 3 Mar 94 p B2 </F>
<F P=103> PY1103183394 </F>
<F P=104>  Santiago EL MERCURIO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Fruit Exporters Association President Ronald Bown 
and Fruits Producers Federation President Ricardo Ariztia have 
expressed satisfaction over the decision handed down on 24 
February by the Philadelphia Appellate Court rejecting the 
jurisdiction immunity requested by the U.S. Government in the 
case of the "poisoned grapes" case. They said the only concrete 
possibility now is to continue the trial "come what may." 
  The two executives discard the possibility of reaching 
agreement with the Clinton administration. During recent 
negotiations with the Chilean Foreign Ministry, the U.S. 
Administration offered grants and general benefits that do not 
compensate the damage suffered by that sector. They noted they 
have not accepted this solution. 
  Ariztia said the judicial process involves about 2,200 
producers and 108 export companies. He added that the private 
sector has invested more than $3 million in the legal process 
and that enough resources are left to carry on for at least one 
more year. Bown said the private fruit producers and exporters 
have demanded an indemnity of $212 million, while some shipping 
lines like the Sudamericana and importers in the United States 
want $230 million. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

