<F P=100> Panama </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Panamanian Electoral Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1103172994 </F>
<F P=103> PA1103172994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on developments related to the Panamanian elections 
scheduled for 8 May 1994. 
  During the Chiriqui province chapter of CADE [Annual 
Conference of Business Executives] '94, held at the Bambito 
Hotel, presidential candidate Ruben Dario Carles (for the 
National Renewal Movement, Nationalist Liberal Republican 
Movement, and Civic Renewal Party that comprise the Change '94 
alliance) announced that he wants to establish a commission to 
promote investments and jobs, "so that local and foreign 
investors will not be lost like someone in the woods who doesn't 
know where to go." Samuel Lewis Galindo, presidential candidate 
for the Solidarity Party and the National Unity Mission that 
comprise the National Consensus Alliance, promised he would 
lower taxes on agricultural supplies to lower production costs. 
"We would do this also by supporting and promoting the 
appropriate producer organizations by giving them training and 
orientation, as well as any technical and financial support they 
may need." Christian Democratic Party presidential candidate 
Eduardo Vallarino said: "Not being prepared for economic 
aperture means certain death for the small production that still 
exists in primary and secondary sectors." Ernesto Perez 
Balladares, presidential candidate for the Democratic 
Revolutionary Party (PRD), Labor Party, and the Liberal 
Republican Party that comprise the United People alliance, 
announced that he would create "irrigation provinces [provincias 
de riego]." "Another element would be the development of 
business organizations." The candidates concurred on the need 
to decentralize public administration to expedite the autonomous 
development of provinces, to protect national production, 
improve the country's road infrastructure to and from Bocas del 
Toro and Chiriqui, and upgrade ports on the Atlantic and Pacific 
coasts. (Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 
28 February 94) 
  Four presidential candidates -- Jose Salvador Munoz, of the 
Doctrinaire Panamenist Party; Eduardo Vallarino; Ernesto Perez 
Balladares, and Ruben Carles -- have said that the Panamanian 
Banking Center is solid and efficient, while acknowledging that 
it must undergo some reforms to consolidate its prestige at the 
national and international level. The candidates conveyed this 
position on 8 March at a meeting organized by the National 
Banking Association. (Panama City LA PRENSA in Spanish 9 March 
94 p 1A) 
  The Change '94 presidential slate presented unveiled its 
platform at a 3 March news conference. The plan "will promote 
the creation of more and better jobs in different sectors and 
improve the quality of current jobs, emphasizing different 
training and job education programs. It will maintain the 
13-month bonus and continue paying workers their second 
allotment of the 13-month bonus," Carles said. (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 3 March 94) 
  A report detailing Carles' position on corruption 
highlighted 
the following points: As a result of the corruption that 
prevailed during the military dictatorship, the Panamanian state 
ended up "in the service of organized crime both inside and 
outside the country, particularly in drug trafficking and money 
laundering." Carles notes that this is why "the eradication of 
corruption will be a slow, difficult, and complex task, but a 
task that must be tackled." He added: "Public spending and the 
use of state property must be strictly and fiscally controlled." 
(Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 7 March 94 p 10A) 
  Papa Egoro Movement [MPE] presidential candidate Ruben 
Blades has said that now that the political campaign has gotten 
under way "the people will really have choices." In response 
to a reporter's question that his campaign seems to be 
faltering, Blades noted that his is a "new group, and we lack 
the economic means others have in the country's politics. Also 
our group has been organizing as we grow." (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 2 March 94) 
  Ruben Blades has said that newsmen will not accompany him on 
his campaign visits because they work for news media "controlled 
by" political and economic "interests." (Panama City LA PRENSA 
in Spanish 7 March 94 p2) 
  Mireya Moscoso de Gruber, presidential candidate for the 
Arnulfist Party, Authentic Liberal Party, Liberal Party, and the 
Independent Democratic Union that comprise the Democratic 
Alliance, has said that in line with her party's principles, she 
will not participate in public debates. She also indicated it 
is too late now to set up runoffs. (Panama City Circuito RPC 
Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 3 March 94) 
  On 8 March, Gruber came out in favor of a new law on the 
banking system that would check money laundering. Regarding the 
U.S. military bases in Panama, she noted that it is the people 
of Panama who, through a plebiscite, must decide whether the 
bases should stay or go. (Panama City LA ESTRELLA DE PANAMA in 
Spanish 9 March 94 p 1A) 
  The Arnulfist Party announced at a news conference that it 
is 
ready for the 8 May elections. The party already has more than 
10,000 party members to represent the party at voting tables 
throughout the country. (Panama City Circuito RPC Television in 
Spanish 2300 GMT 7 March 94) 
  Galindo has unveiled a plan to decentralize the executive 
branch, giving ministries and autonomous and semiautonomous 
entities the authority to implement their own plans and 
projects. His plan calls for the creation of public security, 
tourism, transportation, communications, environment, and 
finance ministries, as well as a national secretariat attached 
to the Presidency. "We will get nowhere so long as we continue 
to not have a modern and agile government that facilitates 
investment by local and foreign citizens." (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 28 February 94) 
  The National Consensus Alliance candidate has proposed the 
creation of a deputy minister's office to handle drug 
prevention, penalties, and rehabilitation. Galindo said that 
ethics standards in Panamanian banking must be reviewed "to see 
if they should be expanded or if the government may take direct 
legal action to prevent" money laundering. (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 3 March 94) 
  Perez Balladares has reaffirmed the Torrijist doctrine 
during 
a visit Las Palmas District, Veraguas Province. In the company 
of local leaders, the candidate listened to peasants, farmers, 
and Indian representatives discuss their problems. (Panama City 
Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 28 February 94) 
  The United People alliance candidate has said that 
Panamanian 
society "faces an economic and moral crisis" that seriously 
threatens peaceful coexistence. This situation is all the more 
dramatic because in six years the country will assume control 
over the Panama Canal, Perez added. He also decried the 
government's failure to ease the problems of poverty and 
unemployment. (Panama City EL PANAMA AMERICA in Spanish 7 March 
94 p 10a) 
  Perez Balladares has said that the PRD's government platform 
is gaining increasing acceptance among the Panamanian people. 
Polls continue to show him leading in voter approval ratings. 
(Panama City Circuito RPC Television in Spanish 2300 GMT 7 
March 94) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

