<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Insurgent Activities </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1203015994 </F>
<F P=103> PY1203015994 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on insurgent activities in Peru compiled from Peruvian 
papers monitored through 3 March. 
  On 24 February the National Police presented to the press 23 
Shining Path "terrorists" who operated in several provinces of 
Ancash Department. They had perpetrated nearly 50 attacks and 
selective crimes against civilian authorities over the past few 
months. They were arrested after a thorough investigation 
conducted over six months by authorities in the many shantytowns 
of Callejon de Huaylas and Conchucos, and in the Lima provinces 
of Huaura and Barranca. The forces seized a large amount of 
explosives, weapons, subversive propaganda, and maps of various 
public buildings used in attacking civilian authorities in 
Chavin Region. (Lima EXPRESO in Spanish 25 Feb 94 p A14) 
  Lambayeque Superior Court ``faceless'' judges cleared 
physician Victor Echeandia Arellano, lawyer Victor Ciguena 
Campos, and six teachers of the charge of terrorism after they 
had served 14 months in prison. They had been "erroneously 
accused of involvement in terrorist activities." (Lima EXPRESO 
in Spanish 25 Feb 94 p A14) 
  Army personnel have arrested four Tupac Amaru Revolutionary 
Movement members operating in Paucartambo valley and Chanchamayo 
Province, Junin Department. They were identified as Juan Quispe 
Rojas, 28; Celestino Llantoy Duran, 27; Cesar Boza Ccoya, 24; 
and Victor Pardo Vivanco, 24. (Lima EL COMERCIO in Spanish 26 
Feb 94 p A14) 
  On 2 March 30 Shining Path "terrorists" surrendered to the 
military authorities at the Tingo Maria countersubversive base. 
Commander Juan Rivas said that 60 "terrorists" had surrendered 
under the repentance law over the past 72 hours, and that 1,100 
"terrorists," most of them members of the Shining Path 
organization, had surrendered in the first quarter of 1994. 
Among the repentants had been "top leaders" in the subversive 
organization in Upper Huallaga, according to Rivas. (Lima LA 
REPUBLICA in Spanish 3 Mar 94 pp 16-17) 

</TEXT>

