<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Survey Notes Perez de Cuellar Leading Presidential Race </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1503003694 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1859 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1503003694 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A study by the company Imasen [Image and Market 
Sociology] released today shows that former UN Secretary General 
Javier Perez de Cuellar leads voters' preferences for president 
of the Republic by 45.2 percent to 43.4 percent, which 
represents support for President Alberto Fujimori. 
  The survey refers to figures obtained during the first week 
in March and recalls that last January, Perez de Cuellar and 
Fujimori were tied with 43.1 percent each. 
  The survey was conducted after the sale of Telefonica 
Peruana 
and Entel Peru [National Telecommunications Enterprise of Peru] 
to Telefonica de Espana for a total of $2.002 billion, which was 
considered an economic success for Fujimori's government. 
  It must be noted that Perez de Cuellar has been reluctant to 
accept his possible candidacy for the presidency despite Imasen 
results showing that he has more than 45 percent support. 
  The same survey shows that if Fujimori runs against Lima 
Mayor Ricardo Belmont he would obtain 49.6 percent of the votes 
against 31.3 percent for Belmont, who obtained 1.3 percent more 
than in a previous survey. 
  Legislators Fernando Olivera and Enrique Chirinos have said 
that if Fujimori runs for reelection, as authorized by the 1993 
Constitution, he must resign his post six months before, 
according to Olivera, and four months before, according to 
Chirinos. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-10929 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat050_r_94010" </HT>


