<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Investment Promotion Agreement Signed With UK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1103182794 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 0000 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1103182794 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "24 Hours" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Early this morning, Colombia and Great Britain 
signed an agreement to promote and protect investments, just as 
the "24 Hours" newscast has already mentioned in an exclusive 
report. 
  The article on compensation, which had originally delayed 
the 
signing of the agreement eight months ago, now reads as follows: 
  Principle of expropriation with just, adequate, and 
effective 
compensation -- by virtue of this principle acknowledged by the 
Constitution, the state will not expropriate, unless it is of 
public or social interest, foreign capital investments in a 
discriminatory manner or without previously paying fair, 
adequate, and effective compensation. 
  According to some experts, this article runs against the 
spirit of Article 58 of the national Constitution, according to 
which there can be special compensations for the sake of equity. 
Nevertheless, in the agreement signed today in London, Colombia 
promised to always pay compensation. Despite changes made to 
the article that had prompted Britain's original refusal to sign 
the accord, there still places in which it contradicts the 
national Constitution. These contradictions likely will come up 
when the Constitutional Court and Congress review the agreement. 
  [Begin recording of constitutional expert Luis Carlos 
Sachica] A fair, effective, and adequate compensation might turn 
out to be completely different from what the Constitution says 
considers prior compensation -- compensation in which the 
interests of both the community and the affected parties are 
taken into consideration. [end recording] 
  The new agreement basically seeks to protect the interests 
of 
British investors. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

