<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Oil Firms Must Leave When Contracts End </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1303174094 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1303174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The State Council has touched on the most sensitive 
issue for multinational oil companies in Colombia by ruling that 
those companies must leave when their contracts expire. Guido 
Nule Amin, energy and mines minister, fears that the decision 
will scare away foreign capital. 
  The State Council's decision to eliminate the possibility of 
automatically renewing grant contracts signed with Colombia fell 
on the foreign oil companies like a bucket of cold water. 
  [Begin Shell official Luis Enrique Conde recording] Shell 
has 
asked the Colombian Government to extend its contract for 10 
years beginning in 1994. Considering the points we have 
mentioned, Shell expects the government to grant the extension. 
[end recording] 
  Guido Nule Amin, mines and energy minister, believes the 
ruling jeopardizes foreign investment in Colombia. 
  [Begin Nule Amin recording] The disadvantage that the 
ministry and the government see in this ruling is that it 
weakens the relationship with and the expectations of foreign 
investor companies. [end recording] 
  Five contracts signed between Ecopetrol and the 
multinational 
corporations Esso, Texpet, Jocol, and Petronor, which extract 
crude oil in Lower, Middle, and Upper Magdalena and in the 
Catatumbo Basin, will expire this year. Ecopetrol will take 
over all installations and oil fields now in the hands of those 
companies. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

