<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice Foreign Minister Views Kantor's Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1403225194 Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS in Spanish 
1654 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1403225194 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires NOTICIAS ARGENTINAS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 14 Mar (NA) -- Vice Foreign Minister 
Fernando Petrella said today that if Argentina has no medical 
patents law "it will be very difficult to get investments and 
import advanced technology." 
  Petrella said: "If we want to introduce the country into a 
market such as the U.S. market, we cannot go on without a 
patents law." 
  In this regard, U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor 
reportedly told President Carlos Menem in Chile on 11 March that 
if no progress on that law is made in Congress by 30 April, 
Argentina would be eliminated from the list of candidates to 
join NAFTA. 
  Regarding the request made by UN Secretary General 
Butrus-Butrus Ghali that the Argentine Government send more Blue 
Helmets to Bosnia, Petrella said this is "highly gratifying for 
our foreign policy and the Armed Forces, which are the 
participants in this peace process." 
  In comments made in the "Puzzle" program of the Rock and Pop 
FM station, Petrella said our country "conveyed to the United 
Nations that we will only participate if we get weapons similar 
to the ones the other units have." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

