<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Costa Rica </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Costa Rican Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1503135394 </F>
<F P=103> PA1503135394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Costa Rican economic developments monitored through 
15 March. 
  In the past months, the Treasury Ministry has maintained an 
aggressive policy in placing government bonds on the financial 
market. The debt financed by bonds in 1993 was 33 percent higher 
than in 1992. The high interest rates of the bonds have forced 
banks to pay higher rates, therefore loan costs also increase. 
This is bad for investment and production. (San Jose LA NACION 
in Spanish 28 Feb 94 p 39A) 
  According to the treasury minister, although the fiscal 
deficit reached 5 billion colones in January, at the end of the 
year, it should not be higher than 25 billion, which represents 
2 percent of the GDP. The rise in the January deficit was 
because of reduced tax collection, increased salaries in the 
public sector, and $7 million paid toward the Paris Club debt. 
(San Jose LA REPUBLICA in Spanish 1 Mar 94 p 12) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

