<F P=100> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cristiani Rules Out Possibility of Technical Fraud </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1503231894 San Salvador Canal Doce Television in Spanish 
0300 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1503231894 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador Canal Doce Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Up to Date" newscast] </F>
  [Text] President Alfredo Cristiani today assured people 
that the charges made by opposition political parties regarding 
possible technical fraud during the 20 March elections only seek 
to mar the electoral process. 
  The ghost of possible fraud continues to hover in the 
atmosphere a few days before the elections take place. 
Nevertheless, this was ruled out today by President Cristiani 
who assured us there is no basis for fraud charges, rather these 
charges are generated by groups that foresee a negative result 
in the elections. 
  [Begin Cristiani recording] In my opinion, this is a totally 
wrong strategy that seeks to mar an electoral process that has 
been open and has complied with everything. With regard to the 
UN remarks, I believe these are simple excuses given what the 
results could be. [end recording] 
  As far as the problem reported by the FMLN [Farabundo Marti 
National Liberation Front] on the transfer of voting places in 
several hamlets in the Chalatenango Department, President 
Cristiani said that the highest electoral institution was clear 
that this action is not intended to adversely harm or [word 
indistinct] any particular political party. 
  [Begin Cristiani recording] As has been explained, in four 
Chalatenango municipalities the population resides in the 
department's capital city -- at the seat in Chalatenango. More 
people would have to travel if the voting takes place in the 
municipalities than would have to travel from the municipalities 
to Chalatenango given that the voting document indicates the 
voting place. [end recording] 
  Cristiani told the media that the people should feel assured 
because there will be 900 Onusal [UN Observers for El Salvador] 
observers and approximately 3,000 independent observers, who in 
his opinion will be the witnesses to the election's transparency. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

