<H3> <TI>   Caravan Members Visit Santiago de Cuba </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1503143294 Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks in 
Spanish 0100 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1503143294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Tele Rebelde and Cuba Vision Networks </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Five groups of members of the third U.S.-Cuban 
Caravan of Friendship are visiting several Cuban provinces. At 
1030 this morning, 31 members of the caravan, including the 
Reverend Lucius Walker, arrived in Santiago de Cuba. Their 
arrival was welcomed in this way [cheers heard in background] 
and it couldn't have been any different. 
  For the first time, caravan members are visiting several 
provinces. According to the Rev. Walker, the group had to be 
divided. He said that everyone wanted to visit Santiago de Cuba. 
  [Begin Walker recording, in English with superimposed 
translation into Spanish] We had a little revolution among us, 
and of course we won; therefore, it is our privilege to be here 
with you. [end recording] 
  Speaking on behalf of Cuba, Politburo member Esteban Lazo 
Hernandez said: 
  [Begin Lazo recording] We embrace you wholeheartedly and 
greet you on behalf of all the people of Santiago de Cuba. [end 
recording] 
  Jose Marti's mausoleum was the first place they visited, but 
the historical heritage and a cemetery like this have prompted a 
longer visit. They also toured several parts of the city: 
Antonio Maceo Revolution Square, then Cespedes Park. A group of 
citizens who were aware of their visit was waiting for them. 
[cheers and shouts] 
  At the municipal government building, Mayor (Luis Estruch) 
welcomed Walker, who received the city's coat of arms on behalf 
of the group. In the afternoon, the Siboney minifarm and the 26 
de Julio school were included in their agenda. 
  This caravan will be in Santiago de Cuba until next 
Wednesday. For a province with so many things to show, the 
agenda is rather tight and cannot be extended because of the 
tiring trip. Members of the caravan said, however, that they had 
rested sufficiently on the first day to continue. 

</TEXT>

