<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   OAS Commission Requests Withdrawal From CPR Areas </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1503151194 Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO in Spanish 11 
Mar 94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PA1503151194 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Alberto Ramirez Espada] </F>
  [Text] The OAS International Human Rights Commission 
described to President Ramiro de Leon Carpio during a meeting 
held last night at the presidential palace the need for the 
withdrawal of all military detachments located in areas where 
the Communities of Resistant People (CPR) have settled. The 
meeting was held following the conclusion of an OAS visit that 
lasted several days to the areas in conflict. 
  Leo Valle Lanza, president of the international commission, 
indicated they had received reports from the CPR settlers on 
harassment by Army soldiers, mined camps, and restrictions 
placed on their movements. "It is obvious that as a result of 
the proximity of the combat areas, there could be guerrilla 
movements, but this does not necessarily imply the CPR are 
cooperating with the subversives," Valle Lanza added. 
  "The only thing they want is to be recognized as a civilian 
population and for their most basic rights to be respected," 
noted the international official who also indicated President de 
Leon Carpio had confirmed his intentions to respect those 
rights. This is why the OAS delegates consider the 
demobilization of the military detachments near the CPR a top 
priority. Nevertheless, they received Defense Minister Mario 
Rene Enriquez' assurance that no military operation are being 
carried out in those areas. 
  The international commission was made up of Valle Lanza, 
David Padilla, Elizabeth Houppert, and Osvaldo N. Kreiner. The 
commission was accompanied by Fernando Alvarez Guadamuz who 
indicated they had visited Xalbal, Cantabal, Cuarto Pueblo, San 
Francisco Los Angeles, San Luis, and La Esperanza; they also 
spoke to the soldiers of the nearby detachments. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-10989 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat051_g_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-051 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Not Planning Offensive Against CPR </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1503182294 Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO in Spanish 12 
Mar 94 p 5 </F>

<F P=103> PA1503182294 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City SIGLO VEINTIUNO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Yesterday, Vice President Arturo Herbruger Asturias 
denied any possibility that the government and the Army are 
planning an offensive against residents of the Communities of 
Resistant People (CPR). "The Defense Ministry has already denied 
such accusations. It clearly stated that there will not be 
unreasonable actions against them or that there will be any 
persecution," he added. 
  In paid advertisements, CPR members claim that since 10 
February, there have been "large military mobilizations" 
apparently aimed at subjecting them to military control, 
preventing them from rebuilding the Ixcan Grande Cooperative, 
and stopping more refugees from returning. 
  Herbruger noted that far from organizing acts to intimidate 
or affect these people, the government is involved in efforts to 
protect them. 
  Deputy Foreign Minister Bernardo Arevalo also said the 
members of the OAS Inter-American Human Rights Commission 
(CIDH), who recently visited these communities, did not tell the 
Foreign Ministry about similar complaints. Arevalo said that in 
the letter requesting permission to visit the CPR's, the CIDH 
did not mention this as a motive and only limited itself to 
saying that it wanted to observe the reintegration of refugees 
into the communities process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

