<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Embraer Sells 2 EMB-145 Jets to Australia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1503213494 Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO in Portuguese 
12 Mar 94 p B10 </F>

<F P=103> PY1503213494 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo O ESTADO DE SAO PAULO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sao Jose dos Campos -- The Brazilian Aeronautics 
Company (Embraer) has sold the first two units of the 50-seat 
regional transport EMB-145, which is based on the [EMB-120] 
Brasilia plane. The Australian airline company Flight West, 
which intended to purchase four planes, now has decided to 
purchase two planes and place two firm options to purchase two 
more planes. The contract's cost has been estimated at $60 
million. The contract was signed by Flight West Chairman Dennis 
Buchanan. Flight West has been operating both [EMB-110] 
Bandeirante and Brasilia planes for many years. 
  The EMB-145 is Embraer's most daring project and is still in 
its development stage. The EMB-145's initial flight has been 
scheduled for April 1995. Budgeted at $300 million, this 
project has a potential $1 billion market in the next 15 years. 
Each plane is sold for $13 million. Fourteen customers from 
eight countries have confirmed 136 purchase orders. 

</TEXT>

