<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Departments Said To Lack Representation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1503211294 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1503211294 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "National Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The Senate election left a large part of the 
country's poor and neglected portions with no voice at all: 
Putumayo, Caqueta, Guaviare, Choco, Vaupes, Amazonas, Guainia, 
Vichada, Casanare, Arauca, Meta, and Quindio. Meta has Senator 
Jorge Ariel Infante, and Quindio has Samuel Grisales. 
  At the Chamber of Representatives, the dark spots are 
Amazonas, which lost Milquesedec Lopez and Jairo Jose Ruiz 
Medina, Guainia, which lost the seat of Guillermo Britto, and 
Vaupes, which had Alfonso Gonzalez Vargas. These last three 
departments are in a serious situation, if one considers the 
fact they were completely erased from the parliamentary map; 
this shows how the struggle among the traditional politicians to 
get votes from all over the country-- thanks to the nationwide 
electoral conscription--does not always work out, silencing 
regions that have always been forgotten by the state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

