<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister Pardo Rejects Charges Against Armed Forces </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1503223894 Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 in Spanish 1730 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1503223894 </F>
<F P=104>  Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision Television Cadena 
1 </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Defense Minister Rafael Pardo by Sandra </F>
Vergara in Santa Fe de Bogota on 15 January; from the "National 
Newscast" -- recorded] 
  [Text] A short while ago I spoke with Defense Minister 
Rafael Pardo. He reacted to a report that Amnesty 
International has just released in which it directly accuses the 
Colombian Armed Forces of committing most of the political 
crimes and social cleansing homicides in Colombia. 
  [Begin recording] [Pardo] The statistics are being 
manipulated. They cited a number of facts and events and 
accused the military forces of committing crimes that have not 
been tried and for which no sentencing has been handed down. 
With ill intention they mentioned these cases. They claim that 
the military forces are involved. This is evidently highly 
ill-intentioned. 
  [Vergara] That report suggests that the Armed Forces are 
working with paramilitary forces or that they are allied with 
the death squads. 
  [Pardo] I repeat, I know nothing about that report. We will 
react to it as soon as we know about it. The claim that there 
is an alliance between military forces and paramilitary groups 
is absolutely false. Paramilitary groups are not our allies. In 
fact, the Colombian military forces pursue them. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

