<F P=100> Peru </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Arequipa Mayor To Run for Presidency </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1503231994 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0322 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1503231994 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lima, 11 Mar (EFE) -- Luis Caceres Velasquez -- 
former mayor of Arequipa, the second-largest city in Peru -- 
today announced his decision to run for the presidency of his 
country in the 1995 general elections as a candidate for the 
independent movement "Peru in the Year 2000" [Peru al 2000]. 
  Caceres is the first candidate to officially announce his 
intention to run for the presidency in next year's presidential 
and legislative electoral campaign. 
  The former mayor said he has several names to include on his 
list of congressional candidates and already has the name of two 
vice presidents who will run on his presidential ticket. He 
declined, however, to reveal their names. 
  He pointed out that everyone is entitled to become a 
candidate to govern the country and that he is not concerned 
about the possibility that President Alberto Fujimori, whom the 
Constitution allows to be reelected, and former UN Secretary 
General Javier Perez de Cuellar might decide to present their 
candidacies too. 
  Fujimori often has reiterated that he still has not thought 
about the possibility of running for reelection. Nonetheless, 
opposition members believe he surely will. Perez de Cuellar, 
however, has recently said it is still too early to decide on a 
possible candidacy. 
  Caceres Velasquez was mayor of Arequipa, 1,025 km south of 
Lima, for two consecutive terms. In the January 1993 municipal 
elections he was a candidate for mayor of Lima, but another 
independent candidate -- Ricardo Belmont -- won. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-11022 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat051_r_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-051 </AU>
