<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government To Appeal TSE Rejection of Plebiscite Request </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1603041494 Madrid EFE in Spanish 0134 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1603041494 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Quito, 15 Mar (EFE) -- The Ecuadoran Government on 
15 March announced that it will appeal before all legal bodies 
the decision of the Supreme Electoral Tribunal [TSE] to not hold 
a plebiscite on 1 May on constitutional issues requested by 
President Sixto Duran-Ballen. 
  Carlos Larreategui, minister secretary general of public 
administration, made this announcement and pointed out that the 
TSE's decision is "an attack on democracy" stemming from a 
"conspiracy" of the electoral interests of two opposition 
parties, namely the Social Christian Party (PSC) and the 
Democratic Left (ID). 
  In the first public reaction by a government official after 
the TSE decision was revealed, Larreategui said that President 
Duran-Ballen, who is touring Japan and China, will address his 
compatriots on 16 March from Tokyo on the decision made by the 
top electoral tribunal. 
  Vice President Alberto Dahik, the acting chief of state, is 
meeting with several ministers and other officials to discuss 
the situation. 
  The plebiscite requested by Duran-Ballen sought to consult 
Ecuadorans on the reelection of the president and other public 
officials, which is currently banned by the Constitution, and 
also on the term of the mandate and the powers that parliament 
members should have, among other issues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

