<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Aristide Denies Involvement in Alleged Land Deal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1603230894 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1603230894 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] One can only sell what one owns. This is what 
Aristide spokesman Jean-Claude Martineau said to explain to 
public opinion that Jean-Bertrand Aristide has nothing to do 
with the Mole Saint-Nicolas thing, or the (Portortuga) affair. 
The Haitian president is not involved in this matter -- not 
closely nor even remotely -- nor is any other member of the 
government involved in this matter. However, perhaps the main 
person accused, Commerce Minister Louis Dejoie, is. The matter 
is still just a rumor, but it will be looked into, says 
Jean-Claude Martineau. 
  [Begin Martineau recording, in Creole] Something is being 
said discreetly throughout the country: The commerce minister 
has allegedly given a company a portion of Mole Saint-Nicolas. 
The rumor says that no other part of the government knows about 
it. Since this is a rumor, we will try to obtain information 
about it. 
  Meanwhile, however, President Aristide would like to inform 
the public that he has nothing to do with that matter. Should it 
be true, the minister alone must bear full responsibility for 
it. When one does not own land, one cannot sell that land. [end 
recording] 
  Let us recall that during a news conference by the Group of 
Democratic Parliamentarians [Groupe des Parlementaires 
Democrates, GPD], Deputy Samuel Madistin accused the minister of 
commerce of having signed a contract with the company 
(Portortuga S.A.) granting it a portion of Mole Saint-Nicolas. 
This contract allegedly gives the company exclusive rights to 
build an entertainment and leisure facility on land located in 
Mole Saint-Nicolas. 

</TEXT>

