<H4>   Admits Rebel Action in Chiapas </H4>
<F P=102> PA1603180194 Mexico City XEW Television Network in Spanish 
0430 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1603180194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City XEW Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report on Guatemalan President Ramiro de Leon Carpio's </F>
official visit to Mexico City on 15 March; from the "24 Hours" 
newscast; passages within quotation marks are recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] In the afternoon, President 
Ramiro de Leon Carpio met with Mexican Government Secretary 
Jorge Carpizo and Commerce Secretary Jaime Serra Puche. Later at 
a local hotel, he met with reporters and admitted that 
Guatemalan rebels could have provided guidance and weapons 
during the Chiapas conflict. 
  [De Leon] "Just today, we spoke with President Carlos 
Salinas 
de Gortari about the possible involvement of Guatemalans or 
other foreign nationals in the January events. As the defense 
minister has already said, we cannot deny that possibility." 
  During a dinner hosted by the Mexican leader and his wife to 
honor Guatemalan President Ramiro de Leon Carpio and his 
coterie, President Salinas said economic development is a 
guarantee for peace. 
  [Salinas] "This is why it is important to maintain peace as 
an asset of unbreakable unity and a requirement for civilian 
coexistence. For Mexico and all Latin American countries, peace 
with justice is our most valuable heritage." 
  President De Leon Carpio was optimistic about signing a 
peace 
agreement thereby concluding three decades of war between the 
Guatemalan guerrillas and the Army. 
  [De Leon] "The conflict is such that it has hampered any 
possibility of growth and impaired all efforts of moving more 
swiftly toward sustained and sustainable development." 
  Mexican cabinet members and the Guatemalan delegation also 
attended the dinner offered by Mr. and Mrs. Salinas de Gortari 
in honor of the Guatemalan president and his wife, Maria Eugenia 
Morales de Leon Carpio. 

</TEXT>

